The deacon enjoins silence3 for which the Mozarabic formulary is Silentium facite} The bishop salutes the congregation in a formulary preserved by St. Germain and identical with that given in the Mozarabic Liturgy. At Milan it was the custom to use Dominus vobiscum, as at Rome. St. Germain speaks of the salutation only in this place, that is, before the introductory canticles. This is the place also assigned to the first salutation in the Ambrosian Liturgy. In the Mozarabic it is said only aster the collect. In these two liturgies the salutation follows each of the three lections‚2
